Heat your #oven{} to 200C. Halve, peel and chop the @echalion shallot{1} into small
pieces. Peel and grate the @garlic clove{1} (or use a #garlic press{}). Drain and
rinse the @lentils{1} in a #sieve{}.

Heat a #medium saucepan{} on medium heat with a knob of @?butter{a knob} (if you
have some) or a drizzle of @?oil{a drizzle}. When hot, add the shallot and cook,
stirring regularly, until soft, ~{4-5%minutes}. Add half the garlic and cook,
stirring, for ~{1%minute}, then mix through the lentils, @water for the lentils{100}
and @chicken stock powder{1} and stir well. Add @salt{} and @pepper{} to taste.
Bring to a simmer then reduce the heat and cook with a #lid{} on (or cover with
#foil{}) for ~{10%minutes}.

Meanwhile, put a #large frying pan{} on medium-high heat (no oil). Season the
@duck breasts{2} with @salt{}. When hot, fry the duck breasts skin-side down
until the skin is golden, ~{5%minutes}. Turn and cook the flesh side for ~{1%minute}.

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands after handling raw meat.

Transfer to a #roasting tin{} and roast on the top shelf of the oven for
~{10-11%minutes}. Keep the pan and the duck fat, you will need it later!

Add the @wholegrain mustard{1} to the lentils, taste and add more salt or pepper
if needed. Simmer with a lid off for ~{5%minutes} until slightly thickened. Once
the duck is cooked, remove from your oven and rest in a warm place, (wrapped
in #tin foil{} if you have some) for ~{4-5%minutes}.

> IMPORTANT: The duck is cooked when it is no longer pink in the middle.

About 5 mins before you are ready to serve, drain off half of the duck fat from
the pan and return to medium heat. Add the remaining @garlic clove{1} and cook
for ~{1%minute}, stirring regularly, then add the @shredded savoy cabbage{100}
with a pinch of @salt{} and @pepper{} and stirfry for ~{1%minute}. Add a splash
of @water{}, cover with a lid and cook until just tender, ~{2-3%minutes}.

Slice the rested duck. Warm the lentils through if you need to. Serve the lentils
topped with the cabbage and duck slices. Enjoy!